      "id": 1,
      "text": "Fairmount was once called Tyler or Jeromeville, but its post office was renamed Fairmount on January 1, 1846.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fairmount%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "From 1838 until the late 1800s, Fairmount hosted a minor stop on the Auburn‑Syracuse Railroad and later the New York Central.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fairmount%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "South of Fairmount lies Split Rock, once a quarry and early‑20th‑century munitions factory site.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fairmount%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The area, originally part of the New York State Salt Reservation, was annexed to Camillus in 1834.",
